commit.message:
Add cork_strlen function

For strings created using cork_strdup and friends, we were already
keeping the length of the string in memory next to its content.  Let's
make that part of the public API!  The best of both worlds, C strings
and Pascal strings, living together in harmony.
Fix version calculation

Merge branch 'fix-actions'

* fix-actions:
  Generate git versions from out-of-tree builds
  Rebuild autotools scripts correctly in CI

Generate git versions from out-of-tree builds

We have to ensure that the calculate script knows where the source
directory is, so that it can set up $GIT_DIR correctly when generating
git-based version numbers.

Rebuild autotools scripts correctly in CI

We just added a new autogen.sh script, which we should use, instead of
calling autoreconf directly.

Use simpler git post-release version numbers

We don't really need the full git commit information in the dist tarball
names and version numbers.  (We already have the commit available in its
own .commit-stamp file.)  That makes the new distcheck version
comparison logic match more often â€” it should really only be when we cut
a new release that we have to worry about it!

Ensure correct version in dist tarball

That adds an additional dist hook that verifies that the PACKAGE_VERSION
that configure records is the same as the _current_ version reported by
`git describe`.  PACKAGE_VERSION is only updated when _autoconf_ is
run, so if you've made several commits, the version number will be out
of date.  You have to explicitly re-run autogen.sh to regenerate the
correct package version.

h/t https://stackoverflow.com/a/46222039

Merge branch 'array-remove'

* array-remove:
  Add array removal functions

Add array removal functions

You can remove an individual element or a range of them.  If you've
provided a `remove` callback, we'll call it on the removed entries.
Bump library version info for 1.0.0

Merge branch 'likely-slice'

* likely-slice:
  Add cork_slice_advance function
  Add likeliness annotations to slice functions

Add cork_slice_advance function

This is exactly like cork_slice_slice_offset, except that it returns the
slice's buffer from _before_ the call.  This should make deserializing
out of a slice slightly faster.
Add likeliness annotations to slice functions

Merge branch 'inline-buffer'

* inline-buffer:
  Add inline versions of several buffer functions
  Add a clang-format file

Add inline versions of several buffer functions

These have been very stable for several years, and are quite simple.
Let's give callers the ability to inline them.
Add a clang-format file
Add byte-swapping macros for cork_u128

Add shift operators for 128-bit integers (#163)

Logical left- and right-shift

commit.message: Install libcork.pc when using autotools
Install version.h when using autotools

Add CORK_INLINE attribute (#161)

Ideally, we use the C99 `inline` attribute â€” you provide a declaration
_and_ definition of your function in a header file, labeled with the new
CORK_INLINE attribute.  You then provide a copy of the declaration (but
_not_ the definition) in a source file, _without_ the CORK_INLINE
attribute.  That ensures that there's a linkable copy of the function as
part of that source file â€” and that its definition is guaranteed to
match the one in the header file.

If C99 inline isn't available, we fall back on using `static`.  That
means that the function definition will be duplicated in each source
file that uses it, but prevents duplicate symbol definition errors.
(That means you can't rely on being able to take the address of the
inline function, in a way that's consistent across source files, unless
you can guarantee that you're compiling in C99 mode.)

This patch also updates a lot of libcork functions and macros to use the
new attribute.

commit.message:
Use Travis container infrastructure

This should speed up our builds.  The only wrinkle is that we have a
package that we only technically need when performing a 32-bit build.
There's no way (that I know of) to conditionally install that package in
the container world like we were doing before.  But it doesn't hurt
anything to install the package when it's not needed.

commit.message:
Don't link test cases twice

Before we were building and running each test program twice: once via
static linking, and once via shared library linking.  We now use the
Travis build matrix for that (to still verify that we test both kinds of
linking for each new feature), instead of testing both every time you
run `make test`.
